[30;1m31 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35mThe structure of this environment, including some generated migration scripts, looks like::[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m    yourproject/[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35m        alembic/[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m184[0m[34m of [0m[33m2419[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000702[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.DataExfiltration.Environment[0m

  Filename: [33m/alembic-1.15.2/docs/build/tutorial.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m(env|environment).{1,50}(get|post|curl|nc|invoke-restmethod)[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m==========================[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mUsage of Alembic starts with creation of the *Migration Environment*.  This is a directory of script[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mthat is specific to a particular application.   The migration environment is created just once,[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35mand is then maintained along with the application's source code itself.   The environment is[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35mcreated using the ``init`` command of Alembic, and is then customizable to suit the specific[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35mneeds of the application.[0m

[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m348 | [0m[35mwithin the migration file, using the new identifier ``branch_labels``.[0m

[30;1m6131 | [0m[35m      see if they are equivalent.  Other backends may[0m
[30;1m6132 | [0m[35m      need to do the same thing.[0m

[30;1m4632 | [0m[35m      that are named the same as a column are now ignored on[0m
[30;1m4633 | [0m[35m      MySQL if we see that the backend is reporting that it already exists;[0m
[30;1m4634 | [0m[35m      this indicates that we can still detect additions of these indexes[0m
[30;1m4635 | [0m[35m      but not drops, as we cannot distinguish a backend index same-named[0m
[30;1m4636 | [0m[35m      as the column as one that is user generated or mysql-generated.[0m

[30;1m359 | [0m[35mThe issues that arise in this mode are mostly to do with constraints.[0m
[30;1m360 | [0m[35mDatabases such as Postgresql and MySQL with InnoDB will enforce referential[0m
[30;1m361 | [0m[35mintegrity (e.g. via foreign keys) in all cases.   Unlike SQLite, it's not[0m
[30;1m362 | [0m[35mas simple to turn off referential integrity across the board (nor would it[0m
[30;1m363 | [0m[35mbe desirable).    Since a new table is replacing the old one, existing[0m

[30;1m1585 | [0m[35m        sent at the same time.[0m

[30;1m2503 | [0m[35m        Fixed issue where MySQL databases need to use CHANGE COLUMN when altering a[0m
[30;1m2504 | [0m[35m        server default of CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, NOW() and probably other functions[0m

[30;1m2509 | [0m[35m        unconditionally, as in the vast majority of cases the server default is to[0m

[30;1m642 | [0m[35m</div>[0m
[30;1m643 | [0m[35m<p>Replaceable objects present a problem in that in order to make incremental[0m
[30;1m644 | [0m[35mchanges to them, we have to refer to the whole definition at once.[0m
[30;1m645 | [0m[35mIf we need to add a new column to a view, for example, we have to drop[0m
[30;1m646 | [0m[35mit entirely and recreate it fresh with the extra column added, referring to[0m
[30;1m647 | [0m[35mthe whole structure; but to make it even tougher, if we wish to support[0m

[30;1m74 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mThe challenge of SQL script generation is that the scripts we generate can't rely upon[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35many client/server database access.  This means a migration script that pulls some rows[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35minto memory via a ``SELECT`` statement will not work in ``--sql`` mode.   It's also[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35mimportant that the Alembic directives, all of which are designed specifically to work[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35min both "live execution" as well as "offline SQL generation" mode, are used.[0m

[30;1m49 | [0m[35m==========================================[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35mThe ``alembic revision`` command, also available programmatically[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mvia :func:`.command.revision`, essentially produces a single migration[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35mscript after being run.  Whether or not the ``--autogenerate`` option[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mwas specified basically determines if this script is a blank revision[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35mscript with empty ``upgrade()`` and ``downgrade()`` functions, or was[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mproduced with alembic operation directives as the result of autogenerate.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1837[0m[34m of [0m[33m2419[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m34 | [0m[35mbetween a :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.MetaData` object and a database[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mbackend to produce a structure showing how they differ.   The two[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mfunctions provided are :func:`.compare_metadata`, which is more of the[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m"legacy" function that produces diff tuples, and :func:`.produce_migrations`,[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35mwhich produces a structure consisting of operation directives detailed in[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35m:ref:`alembic.operations.toplevel`.[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m257 | [0m[35m  sitting on different heads was basically impossible to reconcile; having[0m
[30;1m258 | [0m[35m  to manually splice the head files together invariably meant that one migration[0m
[30;1m259 | [0m[35m  would occur before the other, thus being incompatible with databases that[0m
[30;1m260 | [0m[35m  were present on the other migration.[0m
[30;1m261 | [0m[35m[0m
